Structural Divergence - Protein dynamics

Maria Laura Marcos, Julian Echave

Introduction

We study the evolutionary divergence of proteins using the LF-ENM and comparing simulated mutants with experimental data.

We studied the globins family. We used the ENM ANM with R0 = 12.5 to generate mutants. We used as reference for the ENM the protein with pdb code 1a4fb. We simulated 10 mutants of this reference for each protein of the family. The globins family is of the type alpha and consists of the following proteins:

 [1] "1bina" "1lh1"  "1hlm"  "1hlb"  "2mm1"  "1pmba" "1ymb"  "1mbs" 
 [9] "1emy"  "1lht"  "1myt"  "2pghb" "2hhbb" "1hdab" "2mhbb" "1hdsb"
[17] "1fdhg" "1spgb" "1hbhb" "1outb" "1spga" "1pbxa" "1hdaa" "2hbg" 
[25] "3sdha" "1mba"  "2hhba" "2mhba" "2pgha" "1hdsa" "1outa" "2lhb" 
[33] "1itha" "1ecd"  "1a4fa" "1a9we" "1hbra" "1a6ma" "1cg5a" "1cg5b"

Structural divergence along normal modes

In this section we consider structural divergence using normal mode coordinates. Pn is the square divergence along a normal mode relative to the mean.
